==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr}} {{term|adverbe}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|adverbium|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad-#Latin|ad-|to|lang=la}} + {{term|verbum||word|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈadvəːb/}}
* {{IPA|/ˈædvəɹb/}}
* {{audio|En-us-adverb.ogg|audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{grammar}} A [[word]] that [[modify|modifies]] a [[verb]], [[adjective]], other adverbs, or various other types of words, [[phrases]], or [[clause]]s.
#* '''1897''', Henry James, ''What Maisie Knew'':
#*: ‘Fortunately your papa appreciates it; he appreciates it ''immensely''’—that was one of the things Miss Overmore also said, with a striking insistence on the '''adverb'''.
#* (''modifying a verb'') ''I '''often''' went outside hiking during my stay in Japan.''
#* (''modifying an adjective'') ''It was '''often''' [[cold]] outside.''
#* (''modifying another adverb'') ''Not '''often'''.''

====Usage notes====
* Adverbs comprise a fundamental category of words in most languages.  In English, adverbs are typically formed from adjectives by appending {{term|-ly}} and are used to modify verbs, [[verb phrase]]s, adjectives, other adverbs, and entire sentences, but not [[noun]]s or [[noun phrase]]s.

